A091042.name: Triangle of even numbered entries of odd numbered rows of Pascal's triangle A007318.

O.g.f. for n-th diagonal: ( Sum_{k = 0..n} binomial(2*n,2*k)*x^k )/(1 - x)^(2*n).

A091043.name: Normalized triangle of odd numbered entries of even numbered rows of Pascal's triangle A007318.
formula: a(n, m)= binomial(2*n, 2*m+1)/(2*b(n)), n>=m+1>=1, else 0, with b(n) := GCD(seq(binomial(2*n, 2*m+1)/2, m=0..n-1)), where GCD denotes the greatest common divisor of a set of numbers (here one half of the odd numbered entries in the even numbered rows of Pascal's triangle). It suffices to consider m=0..floor((n-1)/2) due to symmetry.

A091044.name: One half of odd-numbered entries of even-numbered rows of Pascal's triangle A007318.
formula: T(n, m)= binomial(2*n, 2*m+1)/2, n >= m + 1 >= 1, else 0.
The n-th row polynomial R(n,x) = 1/(4*sqrt(x))*( (1 + sqrt(x))^(2*n) - (sqrt(x) - 1)^(2*n) ) and has n-1 real zeros given by the formula -cot^2(k*Pi/(2*n)) for k = 1,2,...,n-1. Cf A091042.
The row polynomial R(n,x) satisfies (x - 1)^n*R(n,x/(x - 1)) = U(n,2*x - 1), the n-th row polynomial of A053124.
(1) T(n,m) = T(n-1,m) + T(n-1,m-1)*(2*n-1-m)/m for 0 < m < n-1 with T(n,0) = n and T(n,n) = 0;
(3) The row polynomials p(n,x) = Sum_{m=0..n-1} T(n,m)*x^m satisfy the recurrence equation p(n+2,x) = (2+2*x)*p(n+1,x) - (x-1)^2*p(n,x) for n >= 1 with initial values p(1,x) = 1 and p(2,x) = 2+2*x.
G.f.: x*y /(1 - 2*(x+y) + (x-y)^2) with the entries regarded as an infinite square array A(i, j) read by antidiagonals. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 15 2017

A091202.name: Factorization-preserving isomorphism from nonnegative integers to binary codes for polynomials over GF(2).

Other identities. For all n >= 1, the following holds:

A091225(a(n)) = A010051(n). [Maps primes to binary representations of irreducible GF(2) polynomials, A014580, and nonprimes to union of {1} and the binary representations of corresponding reducible polynomials, A091242. The permutations A091204, A106442, A106444, A106446, A235041 and A245703 have the same property.]
For n <= 1, a(n) = n, for n > 1, a(n) = 2*a(n/2) if n is even, and if n is odd, then a(n) = A305421(a(A064989(n))).

A091203.name: Factorization-preserving isomorphism from binary codes of GF(2) polynomials to integers.
formula: a(0)=0, a(1)=1. For n's coding an irreducible polynomial ir_i, that is if n=A014580(i), we have a(n) = A000040(i) and for composite polynomials a(ir_i X ir_j X ...) = p_i * p_j * ..., where p_i = A000040(i) and X stands for carryless multiplication of GF(2)[X] polynomials (A048720) and * for the ordinary multiplication of integers (A004247).
Other identities. For all n >= 1, the following holds:

A010051(a(n)) = A091225(n). [After a(1)=1, maps binary representations of irreducible GF(2) polynomials, A014580, to primes and the binary representations of corresponding reducible polynomials, A091242, to composite numbers. The permutations A091205, A106443, A106445, A106447, A235042 and A245704 have the same property.]
For n <= 1, a(n) = n, for n > 1, a(n) = 2*a(n/2) if n is even, and if n is odd, then a(n) = A003961(a(A305422(n))).

A091204.name: Factorization and index-recursion preserving isomorphism from nonnegative integers to polynomials over GF(2).
formula: a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(p_i) = A014580(a(i)) for primes with index i and for composites a(p_i * p_j * ...) = a(p_i) X a(p_j) X ..., where X stands for carryless multiplication of GF(2)[X] polynomials (A048720).
As a composition of related permutations:
For all n >= 0, the following holds:
a(A007097(n)) = A091230(n). [Maps iterates of primes to the iterates of A014580. Permutation A245703 has the same property]
For all n >= 1, the following holds:

A091225(a(n)) = A010051(n). [Maps primes bijectively to binary representations of irreducible GF(2) polynomials, A014580, and nonprimes to union of {1} and the binary representations of corresponding reducible polynomials, A091242, in some order. The permutations A091202, A106442, A106444, A106446, A235041 and A245703 have the same property.]

A091205.name: Factorization and index-recursion preserving isomorphism from binary codes of GF(2) polynomials to integers.
formula: a(0)=0, a(1)=1. For n that is coding an irreducible polynomial, that is if n = A014580(i), we have a(n) = A000040(a(i)) and for reducible polynomials a(ir_i X ir_j X ...) = a(ir_i) * a(ir_j) * ..., where ir_i = A014580(i), X stands for carryless multiplication of polynomials over GF(2) (A048720) and * for the ordinary multiplication of integers (A004247).
As a composition of related permutations:
For all n >= 0, the following holds:
a(A091230(n)) = A007097(n). [Maps iterates of A014580 to the iterates of primes. Permutation A245704 has the same property.]
For all n >= 1, the following holds:

A010051(a(n)) = A091225(n). [After a(1)=1, maps binary representations of irreducible GF(2) polynomials, A014580, bijectively to primes and the binary representations of corresponding reducible polynomials, A091242, to composite numbers, in some order. The permutations A091203, A106443, A106445, A106447, A235042 and A245704 have the same property.]

formula: G.f.: x/(1+x)/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - x*(3*k+4) - 2*x^2*(k+1)*(k+3)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 03 2013
a(n) = (1/2) * (-1)^n * Phi(2, -n-1, 2), where Phi(z, s, a) is the Lerch transcendantal function. - _Federico Provvedi_, Sep 04 2020

A091349.name: Decimal expansion of Sum_{m>=1, n>=1} 1/(m^2*(m^2 + m*n + n^2)).

A091350.name: First occurrence (*2) of n in A088627 - or - least number that yields n different primes if you factorize it in all possible ways in two factors and add these factors.

A091351.name: Triangle T, read by rows, such that T(n,k) equals the (n-k)-th row sum of T^k, where T^k is the k-th power of T as a lower triangular matrix.
formula: T(n, k) = sum_{j=0..n-k} T(n-k, j)*T(j+k-1, k-1) for n>=k>0 with T(n, 0)=1 (n>=0).
Equals SHIFT_UP(A104445), or A104445(n+1, k) = T(n, k) for n>=k>=0, where triangular matrix X=A104445 satisfies: SHIFT_LEFT_UP(X) = X^2 - X + I.

A091352.name: Row sums of triangle A091351, in which the k-th column lists the row sums of the k-th power of A091351 (when considered as a lower triangular matrix).

A091353.name: Row sums of the matrix square of triangle A091351, in which the k-th column lists the row sums of A091351^k (the k-th power of A091351 when considered as a lower triangular matrix).

A091354.name: Row sums of the matrix cube of triangle A091351, in which the k-th column lists the row sums of A091351^k (the k-th power of A091351 when considered as a lower triangular matrix).

A091355.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of planar partitions of n with k rows.
formula: k-th column is EulerTransform[1, 2, 3, .., k, k, k, ..]-EulerTransform[1, 2, 3, .., k-1, k-1, k-1, ..]. - _Wouter Meeussen_, Aug 29 2004

A091356.name: Number of planar partitions of n with exactly 2 rows.

A091357.name: Number of planar partitions of n with exactly 3 rows.

A091358.name: Number of planar partitions of n with exactly 4 rows.

A091359.name: Number of planar partitions of n with exactly 5 rows.

A091360.name: Partial sums of A000219.
formula: a(n) ~ exp(1/12 + 3 * Zeta(3)^(1/3) * n^(2/3) / 2^(2/3)) / (A * 2^(23/36) * sqrt(3*Pi) * Zeta(3)^(5/36) * n^(13/36)), where Zeta(3) = A002117 and A = A074962 is the Glaisher-Kinkelin constant.

A091361.name: Numbers n such that A001840(n) == 0 (mod n).
formula: G.f.: conjecture: 2*(1+x)/(1-x)/G(0) +x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k+1)/(x*(3*k+4) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 06 2013

A091362.name: Primes p such that the sum of the digits of p is not prime, but the sum of the squares of the digits of p is prime.

A091365.name: Primes p such that the sum of the digits of p is not prime, but the sum of the cubes of the digits of p is prime.

A091366.name: Primes p such that the sum of the cubes of the digits of p is prime.

A091367.name: Primes p such that the sum of the digits raised to the 4th power is prime.

A091368.name: Primes p such that the sum of the digits of p is not prime, but the sum of each digit raised to the 4th power is prime.

A091369.name: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} phi(i)*ceiling(n/i).
formula: a(n) = n^2 - A063985(n). - _Enrique Pérez Herrero_, Feb 25 2012

A091370.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of dissections of a convex n-gon by nonintersecting diagonals, having a k-gon over a fixed edge (base).
formula: G.f.: t^3*z^3*S^2/(1-t*z*S), where S = (1+z-sqrt(1-6*z+z^2))/(4*z) is the g.f. of the little Schroeder numbers (A001003).

A091371.name: Smallest prime factor of n - number of prime factors of n with multiplicity.

A091372.name: Number of numbers <= n having more prime factors than the value of their smallest prime factor.
formula: For any k < 1, a(n) > kn for large enough k. For example, a(n) > n/2 for n > 26474. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Jul 06 2016

A091373.name: Number of numbers <= n having exactly as many prime factors as the value of their smallest prime factor.

A091374.name: Number of numbers <= n having fewer prime factors than the value of their smallest prime factor.

A091375.name: Numbers k with property that the number of prime factors of k (counted with repetition) exceeds the smallest prime factor of k.

A091376.name: Numbers k with property that the number of prime factors of k (counted with repetition) equals the smallest prime factor of k.

A091377.name: Numbers having fewer prime factors than the value of their smallest prime factor.

A091378.name: Triangle read by rows: T(m,n) = number of weak factorization systems (trivial Quillen model structures) on the poset of order-preserving maps from [m] to [n+1] (where [m] denotes the total order on m objects), viewed as a category.
formula: T(m, n) = T(n, m) because the corresponding categories are isomorphic. T(0, n) = T(n, 0) = 1. T(1, n) = T(n, 1) = C(n+1) the (n+1)st Catalan number (A000108).

A091379.name: a(n) = Product_{ p | n } (1 + Legendre(-1,p) ).
formula: Here we use the definition that Legendre(-1, 2) = 1, Legendre(-1, p) = 1 if p == 1 mod 4, = -1 if p == 3 mod 4.

A091380.name: Largest quadratic "mixed" residue modulo the n-th prime (LQxR(p_n)).
formula: a(1)=1; a(n>1)=max{r<p_n | -(r/p_n)=|p_n|_4}, where (r/p_n) is the Legendre symbol and |x|_m is the least absolute residue of x modulo m.

A091382.name: Distance between the sequence of primes and the largest "mixed" quadratic residues modulo the primes (A091380).

A091383.name: Prime numbers where the sequence of largest quadratic "mixed" residues modulo the primes (A091380) is non-monotonic.

A091384.name: Members of the difference sequence (A091381) of the sequence of largest quadratic "mixed" residues modulo the primes (A091380) where the latter is non-monotonic.

A091385.name: Distance (A091382) of primes from the largest quadratic "mixed" residues modulo the primes (A091380), where the latter is non-monotonic.

A091386.name: Solution to the merit factor problem.

A091387.name: Aronson's mod 13 sequence: "T is the first, fourth, eleventh, third, ... letter in this sentence, not counting spaces or commas and all mod 13".

A091388.name: Aronson's mod 14 sequence: "T is the first, fourth, eleventh, third,... letter in this sentence, not counting spaces and commas and all mod 14".

A091389.name: Aronson's mod 15 sequence: "T is the first, fourth, eleventh, first, ... letter in this sentence, not counting spaces and commas and all mod 15".

A091390.name: Aronson's mod 16 sequence: "T is the first, fourth, eleventh, zeroth, ... letter in this sentence, not counting spaces or commas and all mod 16".

A091391.name: Aronson's mod 17 sequence: "T is the first, fourth, eleventh, sixteenth, seventh, ... letter in this sentence, not counting spaces and commas and all mod 17".

A091396.name: a(n) = Product_{ p | n } (1 + Legendre(2,p) ).
formula: Multiplicative with a(2^e)=1, a(p^e)=0 if p mod 8=3 or p mod 8=5 and a(p^e)=2 if p mod 8=1 or p mod 8=7. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Mar 02 2004

A091400.name: a(n) = Product_{ odd primes p | n } (1 + Legendre(-1,p) ).
formula: Here we use the definition that Legendre(-1, 2) = 0, Legendre(-1, p) = 1 if p == 1 mod 4, = -1 if p == 3 mod 4. This is Shimura's definition, which is different from Maple's.
Expansion of (phi(q)^2 - phi(q^9)^2) / 4 in powers of q where phi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
a(n) = Sum_{d|n} b(d)*(-1)^bigomega(d)*moebius(d) where b(2n)=0 and b(2n+1)=(-1)^n. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 17 2016
G.f.: ((Sum_{k in Z} x^k^2)^2 - (Sum_{k in Z} x^(9*k^2))^2) / 4. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 26 2017

A091401.name: Numbers n such that genus of group Gamma_0(n) is zero.

A091403.name: Numbers n such that genus of group Gamma_0(n) is 1.

A091404.name: Numbers n such that genus of group Gamma_0(n) is 2.

A091405.name: Smaller of two consecutive numbers with the same prime signature not occurring earlier.

A091409.name: a(n) is the smallest m such that A090822(m) = n.

A091410.name: Values of n such that len_x(n) = 0 in A090822.

A091411.name: Lengths of the B blocks in analysis of A090822.
formula: This roughly doubles at each step and a(n) -> 1.743349432191828... * 2^n.

A091414.name: Least number that is the sum of n positive n-th powers in at least 2 ways.
formula: a(n) <= A230477(n) for n > 1, with equality at least for n = 2 and inequality at least for n = 3, 4, 5. - _Jonathan Sondow_, Oct 24 2013

A091415.name: Numbers n such that n!*2^n - 1 is prime.

A091416.name: Natural numbers written out and then regrouped into the smallest possible nontrivial blocks such that each begins and ends with the same digit. (Leading zeros omitted and not counted as beginning digit).

A091417.name: Integers n which are not the difference of 2 integers A and B where A is less than or equal to n such that AB+1 and AB-1 are both primes. In other words, the product A*B cannot be the middle integer of a twin prime pair.

A091418.name: Integers n which are not the sum or difference of 2 integers A and B where A is less than or equal to n such that AB+1 and AB-1are both primes. In other words, the product A*B cannot be the middle integer of a twin prime pair.

A091421.name: Numbers n such that n#*2^n - 1 is prime, where n# is product of prime numbers (primorials).

A091422.name: Write the natural numbers in binary, break the result up into blocks of 2 digits each and convert each block back into decimal.

A091424.name: Numbers n such that n#*2^n + 1 is prime, where n# is product of prime numbers (primorial).

A091425.name: Write the natural numbers in a triangle with k digits in the k-th row, as shown below. Sequence gives the leading diagonal.

A091427.name: Write out the primes and then regroup in 3 digit blocks (omitting leading zeros).

A091430.name: Number of Hamiltonian symmetric trivalent (or cubic) connected graphs on 2n nodes (the Foster census).

A091431.name: Happy-go-Lucky numbers: numbers that are both Happy (A007770) and Lucky (A000959).

A091432.name: Happy-go-Lucky primes: primes arising in A091431.

A091434.name: Poincaré series [or Poincare series] (or Molien series) for a certain four-fold wreath product P_4.

A091435.name: Array T(n,k) = n*(n+k), read by antidiagonals.

A091436.name: Nonnegative integers whose name in Hebrew begins with the Hebrew letter "aleph".

A091437.name: Number of bipartite partitions of ceiling(n/2) white objects and floor(n/2) black ones.

A091438.name: Triangle a(n,k) of partitions of n objects of 2 colors, k of which are black and each part with at least one black object.

A091439.name: Least k such that k/phi(k) >= n, where phi is Euler's totient function.

A091440.name: Smallest number m such that m#/phi(m#) >= n, where m# indicates the primorial (A034386) of m and phi is Euler's totient function.

A091441.name: Table (by antidiagonals) of permutations of two types of objects such that each cycle contains at least one object of each type. Each type of object is labeled from its own label set.
formula: T(n,k) = k * T(n-1,k-1) + (n-k+1) * T(n-1,k), T(1,1) = 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 07 2013

A091442.name: Table (by antidiagonals) of permutations of two types of objects such that each cycle contains at least one object of each type. Each type of object is unlabeled.

A091443.name: Multiperfect numbers n which are divisible by sopfr(n) (multiperfect number: sigma(n) = k*n with k integer, sopfr: Sum of prime factors with repetition).

A091444.name: Concatenate binary vectors ordered first by length, then by the number of 1's and finally lexicographically.

A091445.name: Concatenate binary vectors ordered first by length, then by the number of 1's and finally by a 'reverse' lexicographical ordering (read words from right to left).

A091446.name: Concatenate binary vectors ordered first by length, then by the number of 1's and finally by an 'unusual' lexicographical ordering (1 comes before 0).

A091447.name: Concatenate binary vectors ordered first by length, then by the number of 1's and finally by an 'unusual' lexicographical ordering (read words from right to left, 1 comes before 0).

A091448.name: n-th number k such that a1>a2, where [a0,a1,a2,...] is the simple continued fraction of sqrt(k).

A091449.name: Array T(n,k) read by antidiagonals, where row n is the increasing sequence of numbers k for which the simple continued fraction of sqrt(k) has period n.

A091450.name: Transpose of A091449: array T(n,k) read by antidiagonals, where column n is the increasing sequence of numbers k for which the simple continued fraction of sqrt(k) has period n.

A091451.name: Array T(n,k) read by antidiagonals: (row 0)=squares, (row 1)={numbers m for which the simple continued fraction (CF) of sqrt(m) has period length 1; once (row n) is defined, let (row n+1) begin with the least positive integer not already in a row and let the rest of (row n+1) be the other k's for which CF(sqrt(k)) has the same period length.

A091452.name: Transpose of array in A091451 associated with period lengths of square roots of positive integers.

A091453.name: Triangular array T(n,k) read by rows in which row n consists of the numbers floor(2n/k), k=1,2,...,2n+1.
formula: a(n) = floor(1/(sqrt(n)-floor(sqrt(n)))) for n not a square; a(n) = 0 otherwise. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Oct 02 2019

A091455.name: Integers n such that 3*phi(n) < n that are not multiples of smaller integers with this property.

A091456.name: Least number k such that n * phi(k) < k, where phi is Euler's totient function.

A091457.name: Greatest numerator of the remainder in a reciprocal expansion of 1.
formula: Let 1 = 1/x_1 + ... + 1/x_{n-1} + p/q, where 1/x_1>=...>=1/x_{n-1}>=p/q and (p, q)=1. a(n) = maximal p over all such expansions. Corresponded denominators sequence is A091458.

A091458.name: Denominators corresponding to A091457.
formula: Let 1 = 1/x_1 + ... + 1/x_{n-1} + p/q, where 1/x_1>=...>=1/x_{n-1}>=p/q and (p, q)=1. a(n) = q corresponding to maximal p (=A091457(n)) over all such expansions.

A091459.name: Numbers n such that n-1, n and n+1 can be expressed as a sum of 2 squares in at least 2 ways.

A091460.name: Greatest size of an arithmetic progression contained as substrings in binary representation of n.

A091461.name: Smallest number containing in its binary representation substrings forming an arithmetic progression exactly of size n.

A091462.name: a(n) is the smallest j such that 1/3 + 1/6 + 1/9 + ... + 1/j exceeds n.
formula: The next term is approximately the previous term * e^3.

A091463.name: a(n) is the smallest j such that 1/1 + 1/4 + 1/7 + ... + 1/j exceeds n.
formula: The next term is approximately the previous term * e^3.

A091464.name: a(n) is the smallest j such that 1/2 + 1/5 + 1/8 + ... + 1/j exceeds n.
formula: The next term is approximately the previous term * e^3.

A091466.name: Table (by antidiagonals) of labeled alternating octupi with n black nodes and k white nodes. Each type of object labeled from its own label set.

A091467.name: Table (by antidiagonals) of unlabeled alternating octupi with n black nodes and k white nodes.

A091468.name: Number of unlabeled alternating octupi with n black nodes and n white nodes.

A091469.name: Number of unlabeled alternating octupi with n black nodes.
formula: CIK transform of A016825(n+1) i.e. b(n)=4n-2.

A091470.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {-1,0,1} that are diagonalizable over the complex numbers.

A091471.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {-1,1} that are diagonalizable over the complex numbers.

A091472.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {0,1} that are diagonalizable over the complex numbers.

A091475.name: Decimal expansion of Catalan - Pi^2/16 + Pi*log(2)/4.
formula: Equals Integral_{t=0..1} arctan(t)^2/t^2 dt. - _Amiram Eldar_, May 24 2021

A091476.name: Decimal expansion of Pi^2/4.
formula: Equals integral(x=0..1) log((1+x)/(1-x))/x dx. - _Jean-François Alcover_, May 13 2013
Equals integral_{x=0..infinity} K_0(x)^2 dx, where K_0 is a modified Bessel function (see Gradstein-Ryshik 6.576.4). - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 09 2015
Equals A003881 * A000796. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 09 2015
Pi^2/4 = Integral_{x = 0..inf} x/sinh(x) dx. More generally, Pi^2/4 = 2*(1 + 1/3^2 + ... + 1/(2*n-1)^2) + Integral_{x = 0..inf} exp(-2*n*x)*x/sinh(x). - _Peter Bala_, Nov 05 2019
Equals Integral_{x=0..oo} log(x)/(x^2 - 1) dx. - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 12 2020

A091478.name: Table of graphs with n (>=1) nodes and k (>=0) edges. Each type of object labeled from its own label set.

A091479.name: Number of graphs with n nodes. Nodes and edges labeled each from their own label set.

A091480.name: Table of multigraphs (by antidiagonals) with n (>=1) nodes and k (>=0) edges. Each type of object labeled from its own label set.

A091481.name: Number of labeled rooted 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).
formula: a(n) = i^(n-1)*n^((n-1)/2)*He_{n-1}(-sqrt(-n)), i=sqrt(-1), He_k unitary Hermite polynomial (cf. A066325).

A091484.name: Recamán's Fibonacci variation : a(1)=a(2)=1 then a(n) = a(n-1)+a(n-2)-F(n) if that number is >0 and not already in the sequence; a(n) = a(n-1)+a(n-2)+F(n) otherwise where F(n) denotes the n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: With phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2 for n>1 : a(4n)=floor(r*phi^(4n)) where r = (-675+327*sqrt(5))/90; a(4n+1)=floor(s*phi^(4n+1)) where s=(-132+66*sqrt(5))/18; a(4n+2)=floor(s*phi^(4n+2)) where t= (-15+7*sqrt(5))/2; a(4n+3)=floor(u*phi^(4n+3)) where u=(-115+52*sqrt(5))/15.
For n>=3, the sequence satisfies the order 8 linear recurrence: a(n+8)-7*a(n+4)+a(n)=0. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Apr 30 2006

A091485.name: Number of labeled 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).
formula: E.g.f. satisfies: A(x) = exp( x*A(x) + x^2*A(x)^2/2 ).

A091486.name: Number of unlabeled rooted 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).
formula: Shifts left under transform T where Ta = EULER(E_1, 2(a)). E_1, 2(a) has g.f. A(x)+(A(x^2)+A(x)^2)/2.

A091487.name: Number of unlabeled 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).

A091488.name: Number of asymmetric rooted 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).
formula: Shifts left under transform T where Ta = WEIGH(W_1, 2(a)). W_1, 2(a) has g.f. A(x)+(A(x^2)-A(x)^2)/2.

A091489.name: Number of asymmetric 2,3 cacti (triangular cacti with bridges).

A091490.name: Primes p such that all prime divisors of p^2 + p + 1 are less than p.

A091491.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th diagonal is generated from the n-th row by the sum of the products of the n-th row terms with binomial coefficients.
formula: T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + T(n, k+1) for n>0, with T(n, 0)=1.
Recurrence: for k>0, T(n, k) = Sum_{j=k..n} T(n-1, j). - _Ralf Stephan_, Apr 27 2004
T(n,k) = k * Sum_{i=0..n-k} binomial(2*(n-i)-k-1, n-i-1)/(n-i) for k>0; T(n,0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 07 2011

The n-th row of the triangle is the top row of M^n, where M is the following infinite square production matrix in which a column of (1,0,0,0,...) is prepended to an infinite lower triangular matrix of all 1's and the rest zeros:

A091492.name: Triangle, read by rows, generated recursively and related to partitions.

A091494.name: Decimal expansion of the difference between Pi/8 (A019675) and A091473.

A091495.name: Odd, squarefree n such that n/phi(n) > 2, where phi is Euler's totient function.

A091496.name: a(n) = ((5n)!/(n!(2n)!))(gamma(1+n/2)/gamma(1+5n/2)).
formula: It follows that the o.g.f. for this sequence is the diagonal of the bivariate rational generating function 1/2*( 1/(1 - t*H(sqrt(x))) + 1/(1 - t*H(-sqrt(x))) ) and hence is algebraic by Stanley 1999, Theorem 6.33, p. 197.
Let F(x) = 1/x*Series_Reversion( x*sqrt((1 - x)/(1 + x)^5) ) and put G(x) = 1 + x*d/dx(Log(F(x)). Then A(x) satisfies A(x^2) = (G(x) + G(-x))/2. (End)

A091497.name: Number of nonzero terms in the n-th row of triangle A091492.

A091498.name: The sixth column of triangle A091492, excluding leading zeros.

A091499.name: Triangle, read by rows, such that T(n,k) equals the k-th term of the convolution of the two prior rows indexed by (n-k) and (k-1).
formula: T(n, k) = Sum T(n-k, j)*T(k-1, k-j-1) {j=0..min(n-k, k)}, with T(n, 0)=1, T(n, n)=1 for n>=0.

A091500.name: Convergent of rows in triangle A091499, in which A091499(n,k) equals the k-th term of the convolution of the two prior rows indexed by (n-k) and (k-1).

A091501.name: Row sums of triangle A091499, in which A091499(n,k) equals the k-th term of the convolution of the two prior rows indexed by (n-k) and (k-1).

A091502.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {-1,0,1} that are diagonalizable over the real numbers.

A091503.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {-1,1} that are diagonalizable over the real numbers.

A091504.name: Number of n X n matrices with entries {0,1} that are diagonalizable over the real numbers.

A091506.name: Decimal expansion of (2 + sqrt(2) + 5*arcsinh(1))/9.
formula: Also equals (2 + sqrt(2) + 5*log(1 + sqrt(2)))/9. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Feb 14 2014
James D. Klein proved that this constant is equal to 2/3*int(int(sqrt(x^2 + y^2), x = 0..1), y = 0..1) + 1/3*int(int(sqrt(1 + (y - u)^2), u = 0..1), y = 0..1). - _John M. Campbell_, Apr 02 2016

A091507.name: Product of the anti-divisors of n.

A091508.name: Let b(1)=n; b(k+1)=b(k)/gcd(k,b(k)) if gcd(k,b(k))>1; b(k+1)=b(k)+k otherwise, sequence gives least k such that b(k)=1.

A091509.name: Numbers (in ascending order, without multiplicity) which occur in triples a,b,c such that a < b < c, (b * c) / (b + c) leaves a, (a * c) / (a + c) leaves b and (a * b) / (a + b) leaves c as a remainder.

A091510.name: Number of nonisomorphic algebras with a ternary operation (3-d groupoids) with n elements.

A091511.name: Number of n X n X n 3-D matrices over symbol set {1,...,n} equivalent under any permutation of rows, columns, stacks or the symbol set.

A091512.name: a(n) is the largest integer m such that 2^m divides (2*n)^n, i.e., the exponent of 2 in (2*n)^n.
formula: Mobius transform of A162728, where x/(1-x)^2 = Sum_{n>=1} A162728(n)*x^n/(1+x^n). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jul 12 2009
a((2*n-1)*2^p) = (2*n-1)*(p+1)*2^p, p >= 0. Observe that a(2^p) = A001787(p+1). - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Feb 08 2013

A091513.name: Numbers n such that (2^n + 1)^2 - 2 = 4^n + 2^(n+1) - 1 is prime.

A091515.name: Numbers n such that (2^n - 1)^2 - 2 = 4^n - 2^(n+1) - 1 is prime.

A091517.name: Decimal expansion of the value of r corresponding to the onset of the period 16-cycle in the logistic map.

A091518.name: Decimal expansion of the hyperbolic volume of the figure eight knot complement.

A091520.name: Expansion of 1 / ((1 - 4*x) * sqrt(1 + 4*x)) in powers of x.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) = 2 * a(n-1) + 8 * (2*n - 1) * a(n-2).
G.f.: 1/((1-4*x)*sqrt(1+4*x)) = 1/(1-4*x+2*x*(1-4*x)/G(0)) ; G(k) = 1 + x/G(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 21 2011

A091521.name: Number of configurations of a variant of the 3-dimensional 3 X 3 X 3 sliding cube puzzle that require a minimum of n moves to be reached, starting with the empty space at the center of one of the 6 faces of the combination cube.

A091524.name: a(m) is the multiplier of sqrt(2) in the constant alpha(m) = a(m)*sqrt(2) - b(m), where alpha(m) is the value of the constant determined by the binary bits in the recurrence associated with the Graham-Pollak sequence.
formula: Sequence is completely defined by: a(floor(n*(1+sqrt(2))))=n; a(floor(n*(1+1/sqrt(2))))=n, n>=1 since A003151 and A003152 are Beatty sequences partitioning the integers. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 13 2007

A091527.name: a(n) = ((3*n)!/n!^2)*(Gamma(1+n/2)/Gamma(1+3n/2)).
formula: exp( Sum_{n >= 1} a(n)*x^n/n ) = 1 + 4*x + 23*x^2 + 156*x^3 + 1162*x^4 + 9192*x^5 + ... is the o.g.f. for A007297 (but with an offset of 0). (End)
G.f.: x*B'(x)/B(x), where x*B(x)+1 is g.f. of A007297. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Oct 02 2015
The o.g.f. is the diagonal of the bivariate rational function 1/(1 - t*(1 + x)^3/(1 - x)) and hence is algebraic by Stanley 1999, Theorem 6.33, p. 197. (End)
a(n) = 4^n*2*(n+1)*binomial((3*n-1)/2, n+1)/(n-1) for n >= 2. - _Peter Luschny_, Feb 03 2020

A091528.name: Sum {k=1 to n} H(k) k! (n-k)! (mod {n+1}), where H(k) is the k-th harmonic number.
formula: It appears that the sum {k=1 to n} H(k) k! (n-k)! (mod {n+1}) is congruent to n!*h(n) (mod {n+1}) where h(n) = (1/2)H(n/2) for even n and h(n) = H(n) - (1/2)H(floor(n/2)) for odd n.

A091529.name: When sum {k=1 to n} H(k) k! (n-k)! (mod {n+1}) (A091528) is not zero.

A091530.name: Sum {k=1 to n} H(k) k! (n-k)!, where H(k) is the k-th harmonic number.

Sum_{k = 0..n} T(n,k)*x^k = A000045(n+1), A015518(n+1), A015524(n+1), A200069(n+1) for x = 0, 1, 2, 3 respectively. - _Philippe Deléham_, Oct 30 2013

A091534.name: Generalized Stirling2 array (5,2).
formula: a(n, k)=(((-1)^k)/k!)*sum(((-1)^p)*binomial(k, p)*product(fallfac(p+3*(j-1), 2), j=1..n), p=2..k), n>=1, 2<=k<=2*n, else 0. From eq. (12) of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=5, s=2.

Recursion: a(n, k)=sum(binomial(2, p)*fallfac(3*(n-1)+k-p, 2-p)*a(n-1, k-p), p=0..2), n>=2, 2<=k<=2*n, a(1, 2)=1, else 0. Rewritten from eq.(19) of the Schork reference with r=5, s=2. fallfac(n, m) := A008279(n, m) (falling factorials triangle).

A091536.name: Weight distribution of [89,45,17] binary quadratic-residue (or QR) code.

A091537.name: Alternating row sums of array A091534 (generalized Stirling2 array (5,2)).

A091538.name: Triangle built from m-primes as columns.
formula: For n>=m>=1: a(n, m)= (n-m+1)-th member in the strictly monotonically increasing sequence of numbers N satisfying: N=product(p(k)^(e_k), k=1..) with p(k) := A000040(k) (k-th prime) such that sum(e_k, k=1..) = m, where the e_k are nonnegative. if m=0 : a(n, 0)=1 if n=0 else 0. If n<m then a(n, m)=0.

A091539.name: Second column (k=3) of array A091534 ((5,2)-Stirling2) divided by 10.
formula: a(n)= product(3*j+2, j=0..n-1)*(product(3*(j+1), j=0..n-1) - 3*product(3*j+1, j=0..n-1))/(3!*10). From eq.(12) of the Blasiak et reference(see A091534) for r=5, s=2 and k=3.
a(n)= (3^(2*n))*risefac(2/3, n)*(n!-3*risefac(1/3, n))/(3!*10), with risefac(x, n)=pochhammer(x, n).

A091540.name: Rescaled second column A091539 of array A091534 ((5,2)-Stirling2).
formula: a(n)= (5*2/fac3(3*n-1))*A091539(n), n>=2, with fac3(3*n-1) := A008544(n) (triple factorials).

A091541.name: Four times triple factorials (3*n-2)!!! with leading 1 added.
formula: G.f.: 3-G(0), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(3*k-2)/(x*(3*k-2) + 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jun 11 2013

A091542.name: a(n) = floor( |n * sin(n)| ), where n is in radians.

A091543.name: Triangle built from first column sequences of generalized Stirling2 arrays (m+2,2)-Stirling2, m>=0.
formula: a(n, m)= m^(2*(n-m))*pochhammer(1/m, n-m)*pochhammer(2/m, n-m)/2 if n-1>= m>=1; a(n, 0)= 2^(n-1); else 0.
E.g.f. for m=1, 2, ... column (without leading zeros and offset n=1): (hypergeom([1/m, 2/m], [], (m^2)*x)-1)/2.
G.f. for m=1 column: x/(1-2*x); e.g.f.: (exp(2*x)-1)/2.
a(n, m)= product((m*j+2)*(m*j+1), j=0..n-m-1)/2, n>=m+1>=1, else 0. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=m+2, s=2, k=2.

A091544.name: First column sequence of array A091746 ((6,2)-Stirling2).
formula: a(n)= 2^(n-1)*product((2*j+1)*(4*j+1), j=0..n-1), n>=1. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=6, s=2, k=1.
a(n)= (2^(4*n-1))*risefac(1/4, n)*risefac(1/2, n), n>=1, with risefac(x, n) = Pochhammer(x, n).
a(n)= fac4(4*n-3)*fac4(4*n-2)/2, n>=1, with fac4(4*n-3)=A007696(n) and fac4(4*n-2)/2=A000407(n+1) (quartic- or 4-factorials).

A091545.name: First column sequence of the array (7,2)-Stirling2 A091747.
formula: a(n)= product((5*j+2)*(5*j+1), j=0..n-1)/2, n>=1. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=7, s=2, k=1.
a(n)= (5^(2*n))*risefac(1/5, n)*risefac(2/5, n)/2, n>=1, with risefac(x, n) = Pochhammer(x, n).

A091546.name: First column of the array A092077 ((8,2)-Stirling2).
formula: a(n)= (2^(n-1))*product((3*j+1)*(6*j+1), j=0..n-1), n>=1. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference with r=8, s=2, k=1.
a(n)= (6^(2*n))*risefac(1/6, n)*risefac(1/3, n)/2, n>=1, with risefac(x, n) = Pochhammer(x, n).

A091548.name: Alternating row sums of triangle A091543.

A091549.name: Second column (k=3) sequence of array A078740 ((3,2)-Stirling2) divided by 6.

A091550.name: Second column (k=3) sequence of array A091746 ((6,2)-Stirling2) divided by 12.
formula: a(n)=(2^(4*n))*risefac(1/2, n)*(-3*risefac(1/4, n) + risefac(3/4, n))/(3!*12), n>=2, with risefac(x, n)=Pochhammer(x, n).
a(n)=(2^n)*product(2*j+1, j=0..n-1)* (-3*product(4*j+1, j=0..n-1) + product(4*j+3, j=0..n-1))/(3!*12), n>=2. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference given in A078740 with r=6, s=2, k=3.

A091551.name: Second column (k=3) sequence of array ((7,2)-Stirling2) divided by 14.
formula: a(n)= product(5*j+2, j=0..n-1)*(-3*product(5*j+1, j=0..n-1) + product(5*j+3, j=0..n-1))/(3!*14), n>=2. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference given in A007840 with r=7, s=2, k=3.
a(n)= (5^(2*n))*risefac(2/5, n)*(-3*risefac(1/5, n) + risefac(3/5, n))/(3!*14), n>=2, with risefac(x, n)=Pochhammer(x, n).

A091552.name: Second column (k=3) sequence of array A092077 ((8,2)-Stirling2) divided by 16.
formula: a(n)= (2^n)*product(3*j+1, j=0..n-1)*(-3*product(6*j+1, j=0..n-1) + product(6*j+3, j=0..n-1))/(3!*16), n>=2. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference given in A078740 with r=8, s=2, k=3.
a(n)=(2^(2*n-5))*(3^(2*n-1))*risefac(1/3, n)*(-3*risefac(1/6, n) + risefac(1/2, n)), n>=2, with risefac(x, n)=Pochhammer(x, n).

A091553.name: Third column (k=6) sequence of array A090214 ((4,4)-Stirling2) divided by 72.
formula: G.f.: (1+200*x)/product(1-fallfac(p, 4)*x, p=4..6), with fallfac(n, m) := A008279(n, m) (falling factorials).
a(n)= ((4!)^n)*(1-2*5^(n+1)+binomial(6, 2)^(n+1))/3!. From eq.12 of the Blasiak et al. reference given in A078740 with r=4=s, k=6.

A091732.name: Iphi(n): infinitary analog of Euler's phi function.
formula: Consider the set, I, of integers of the form p^(2^j), where p is any prime and j >= 0. Let n > 1. From the fundamental theorem of arithmetic and the fact that the binary representation of any integer is unique, it follows that n can be uniquely factored as a product of distinct elements of I. If n = P_1*P_2*...*P_t, where each P_j is in I, then iphi(n) = Product_{j=1..t} (P_j - 1).

Thus we have the following analog of the formula phi(n) = n*Product_{p prime divisors of n} (1-1/p): if the factorization of n over distinct terms of A050376 is n = Product(q) (this factorization is unique), then a(n) = n*Product(1-1/q). Thus a(n) is infinitary multiplicative, i.e., if n_1 and n_2 have no common i-divisors, then a(n_1*n_2) = a(n_1)*a(n_2). Now we see that this property is stronger than the usual multiplicativity, therefore a(n) is a multiplicative arithmetic function.

Add that Sum_{d runs i-divisors of n} a(d)=n and a(n) = n*Sum_{d runs i-divisors of n} A064179(d)/d. The latter formulas are analogs of the corresponding formulas for phi(n): Sum_{d|n} phi(d) = n and phi(n) = n*Sum_{d|n} mu(d)/d. (End).

Recurrence (Carlitz): a(n m) = a(n-1, m-2) - 2*(3*n - (m +2))*a(n-1, m-1) + (3*n - (m + 3))*(3*n - (m + 2))*a(n-1, m), for n >= 2, m >= 1, and a(n, m) = 0 if m <= 1 or m > 2*n, and a(1, 2) = 1. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Dec 16 2019

a(n, m) = T(3*n - m - 1, m - 2), for n > = 1 and m = 2, 3, ..., 2*n, with the irregular triangle defined by (-1)^n*exp(x^3/3)*(d/dx)^n exp(-x^3/3) = RT(n, x) = Sum_{k=0..2*n} T(n, k)*x^k, for n >= 0. For T(n, k) see A331816.

The recurrence RT(n, x) = x^2*RT(n-1, x) - (d/dx)RT(n-1, x), n >= 1, with RT(0, x) = 1, implies the T recurrence T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-2) - (k+1)*T(n-1, k+1), for n >= 1, with T(0, 0) = 1, and T(n, m) = 0 for m < 0 and m > 2*n. Also, by induction over n: RT(n, x) = x^2*RT(n-1, x) - 2*(n-1)*x*RT(n-2, x) + (n-1)*(n-2)*RT(n-3, x), using the former recurrence and inserting the derivatives. This translates to an obvious further recurrence for the irregular triangle T. It is used in order to prove the Carlitz recurrence for the index shifted aHat(n, m) = a(n+1, m + 2).
The e.g.f. of the irregular triangle, that is of the row polynomials RT, is E(t, x) = exp((x^3 - (x - t)^3)/3). See the comment above for a proof (setting s=2 there).
The explicit form is a(n, m) = (-1)^m*(3*n - m - 1)!/(3^(n-1)*(n-1)!)*Sum_{j=0..floor((m-2)/3)} (-1)^j*binomial(n-1, j)*binomial(3*(n-1-j), m -2 - 3*j), for n >= 1, and 2 <= m <= 2*n.

A091814.name: Numerator of I(n) = (integral_{x=0..1/2}(1-x^2)^n,dx), where the denominator is b(n) = 2^n*(2*n+2)!/(n+1)!.
formula: a(n) = 2^(n-1)*((2n)!/n!)*J(n) where J(n) = integral( t=0, Pi/6, cos(t)^(2n-1) dt) is given by the order-2 recursion: J(1)=1/2, J(2)=11/24, J(n) = 1/(8*n-4)*((14*n-17)*J(n-1) - 6*(n-2)*J(n-1)). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Sep 30 2006

A091815.name: Numbers n such that numerator of sum(i=1,n,(i-1)/i) is prime.

A091816.name: Numbers n such that numerator of sum(i=1,n,(i+1)/i) is prime.

A091818.name: Sum of even proper divisors of 2n. Sum of the even divisors of 2n that are less than 2n.

A091819.name: Numbers a(n) that have, in binary, the same number of ones as are in a(n)^2 and which have no nonincreasing binary representation.

A091820.name: Number of ways to reach a sum of n by a down-only cascade through Pascal's Triangle, starting at C(0,0)=1 at the apex and shifting left or right by exactly one position at each step.

A091821.name: a(n) counts the one-bits in the binary representation of n when we cycle from left to right through the individual bits of n, restarting at the leftmost bit after the rightmost is reached and performing n bitwise steps in total.

A091823.name: a(n) = 2*n^2 + 3*n - 1.
formula: a(n) = n + 4*binomial(2+n, n), with offset 0. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, May 12 2006
G.f.: x*(4 + x - x^2)/(1 - x)^3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Mar 28 2014

A091824.name: Numbers p such that ((p-1)!*2^(p-1) + 1)/p is a prime.

A091826.name: a(n)=(1/n)*(1+A000254(n)-n) as n runs through the primes.

A091827.name: Least k such that k^n divides A000254(k).

A091831.name: Pierce expansion of 1/sqrt(2).
formula: Let u(0)=sqrt(2) and u(n+1)=u(n)/frac(u(n)) where frac(x) is the fractional part of x, then a(n)=floor(u(n)).

A091832.name: Pierce expansion of 1/e^2.
formula: let u(0)=exp(2) and u(n+1)=u(n)/frac(u(n)) where frac(x) is the fractional part of x, then a(n)=floor(u(n))

A091833.name: Pierce expansion of 1/zeta(2).
formula: let u(0) = Pi^2/6 and u(n+1) = u(n)/frac(u(n)) where frac(x) is the fractional part of x, then a(n) = floor(u(n)).

A091834.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = maximum denominator in the Egyptian fraction representation that minimizes the maximum denominator of the k-th entry of row n of the triangle of numbers 1/2; 1/3, 2/3; 1/4, 2/4, 3/4; ...

A091836.name: A triangle of Motzkin ballot numbers.
formula: G.f.: (1+zM)/(1-tz(1+zM)), where M = 1 + zM+ z ^2M^2 is the g.f. of the Motzkin numbers (A001006).
T(n,m) = (m*(Sum_{k=1..n-m} k*(-1)^(n+m+k)*binomial(n+k-1,n-1) * Sum_{j=0..n-m} binomial(j,-n+m-k+2*j)*binomial(n-m,j)))/(n*(n-m)), n>m, T(n,n)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Aug 20 2012

A091837.name: Smallest b>1 such that 11*n is a repdigit in base b.

A091838.name: a(n) is the number of images of the border correlation function for binary words of length n (cf. link).
formula: a(n) <= F(n) + F(n-2) - m where F(i) is the i-th Fibonacci number and m=2 if n is in the set {2i | i >= 0} - {2^j, 3x2^j | j >= 0}. - Dirk Nowotka (nowotka(AT)utu.fi), May 16 2004
a(n) seems to be asymptotic to phi^n where phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2.

A091839.name: Smoothed version of A091579.
formula: New records (see A091588) first appear at powers of 2. Also a(2n+1) = 1; a(4n+2) = 3; a(8n+4) = 8; etc.

A091840.name: Lengths of suffix blocks associated with A091787.

A091842.name: Lengths of suffix blocks associated with A091799.
formula: a(n) = A091843(valuation(n-1,4)) for n < 259. For larger n, the index n must be increased by the number of terms "200" which occur* up to n-1 (* e.g., at n = 256, 511, 766, 1277, 1532, ...). - _M. F. Hasler_, Aug 09 2018

A091844.name: a(1) = 4. To get a(n+1), write the string a(1)a(2)...a(n) as xy^k for words x and y (where y has positive length) and k is maximized, i.e., k = the maximal number of repeating blocks at the end of the sequence so far. Then a(n+1) = max(k,4).

A091845.name: Records in sequence of lengths of suffix blocks associated with A091844.

A091846.name: Pierce expansion of log(2).
formula: Let u(0)=1/log(2) and u(n+1)=u(n)/frac(u(n)) where frac(x) is the fractional part of x, then a(n)=floor(u(n)).

A091847.name: Perfect totient numbers, omitting powers of 3.

A091848.name: Johnson bound J(n,4,2).
formula: a(n) = n^2/24 - O(n). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 25 2017

A091849.name: Maximal size of (n,4,2) optical orthogonal code.

A091850.name: a(1) = 1; a(n) is the smallest positive integer not already in the sequence such that Sum_{k=1..n} k*a(k) is a prime.

A091851.name: a(1) = 1; then primes associated with A091850.

A091853.name: a(n) is the number of numbers k such that k is obtained by permuting the digits of n and gcd(n,k) > 1.

A091854.name: Index of first occurrence of n in A091853, or 0 if no such number exists.

A091855.name: Odious numbers (see A000069) in A003159.
formula: a(n) is asymptotic to 3*n - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 22 2004

A091856.name: Beginning with 1, minimum value such that gcd(a(2n-1),a(2n)) = 1, gcd(a(2n),a(2n+1))>1 and a(n) > a(n-1).

A091857.name: Beginning with 1, (a(2n-1),a(2n)) = 1, (a(2n),a(2n+1))>1; a(n) is smallest value not yet used that makes this true.

A091859.name: a(1) = 2, a(n) is the least prime of the form 2k*a(n-1)+1 where 2k is the least even number not used earlier.

A091860.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=sum(i=1,n-1,b(i)) where b(i)=0 if a(i) and a(n-i) are both even, b(i)=1 otherwise.
formula: n>1 a(2n)=a(n)+2; if n is a power of 2, a(2n+1)=1+a(2n); if n is the sum of 2 distinct power of 2, a(2n+1)=2+a(2n); a(2n+1)=a(2n) otherwise

A091861.name: a(1) = 1; a(n) = smallest positive unpicked integer such that n-k divides evenly into a(n)*a(k) for every k, 1 <= k <= n-1.

A091862.name: a(n) = 1 if the sum of all exponents of the prime-factorization of n has no carries when summed in base 2, or a(n) = 0 if there are any carries.
formula: If A268374(n) = 0, then a(n) = 1, 0 otherwise. - _Antti Karttunen_, Nov 23 2017

A091864.name: Positive integers n such that Sum_{p<=pi(n)} p = n, where pi(x) denotes the number of primes not exceeding x and the summation is over primes p.

A091866.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of Dyck paths of semilength n having pyramid weight k.
formula: G.f.: G = G(t, z) satisfies z(1-tz)G^2-(1+z-2tz)G+1-tz = 0.

A091867.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of Dyck paths of semilength n having k peaks at odd height.
formula: T(n, k) = [binomial(n+1, k)/(n+1)]*Sum_{j=1..floor((n-k)/2)} binomial(n+1-k, j)*binomial(n-k-j-1, j-1) for k<n; T(n, n) = 1; T(n, k) = 0 for k>n. G.f.=G=G(t, z) satisfies z(1+z-tz)G^2-(1+z-tz)G+1=0. T(n, k)=r(n-k)*binomial(n, k), where r(n)=A005043(n) are the Riordan numbers.
O.g.f.: H(x,t) = {1-sqrt[1-4x/(1-(t-1)x)]}/2 (shifted index, as given in Copeland's comment, see comp. inverse there).
H(x,t)= x / [1-(C.+(t-1))x] = Sum_{n>=1} (C.+ (t-1))^(n-1)*x^n umbrally, e.g., (a.+b.)^2 = a_0*b_2 + 2 a_1*b1_+ a_0*b_2, where (C.)^n = C_n are the Catalan numbers (1,1,2,5,14,..) of A000108.

This shows directly that the lowering operator for the polynomials is D=d/dt, i.e., D p(n,t)= D(C. + (t-1))^n = n * (C. + (t-1))^(n-1) = n*p(n-1,t), so that the polynomials form an Appell sequence, and that p(n,0) gives a Motzkin sum, or Riordan, number A005043.

A091868.name: a(n) = (n!)^(n+1).
formula: a(n) = A000178(n)*A002109(n), i.e., product of superfactorials and hyperfactorials. - _Henry Bottomley_, Nov 13 2009

A091869.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of Dyck paths of semilength n having k peaks at even height.
formula: T(n, k) = binomial(n-1, k)*(Sum_{j=0..ceiling((n-k)/2)} binomial(n-k, j)*binomial(n-k-j, j-1))/(n-k) for 0 <= k < n; T(n, k)=0 for k >= n.
G.f.: G = G(t, z) satisfies z*G^2 - (1 + z - t*z)*G + 1 + z - t*z = 0. T(n, k) = M(n-k-1)*binomial(n-1, k), where M(n) = A001006(n) are the Motzkin numbers.
T(n+1, k+1) = n*T(n, k)/(k+1). - _David Callan_, Dec 09 2004

A091875.name: Square roots of squares in A068176.

A091876.name: Square roots of squares in A068177.

A091878.name: a(n) can be expressed as the difference of the squares of consecutive primes in just four distinct ways.

A091879.name: Sequence of k values arising in A091771.

A091880.name: A049232 indexed by A000040.
formula: a(n) = k such that A000040(k) = A049232(n).

A091884.name: Triangle of numbers defined by Knuth.

A091885.name: Triangle T(n,k) defined by the generating function cosh(sqrt(y)*arcsin(x)) + sqrt(y)*sinh(sqrt(y)*arcsin(x)) - 1 = Sum_{n>=1} Sum_{k=1..n} T(n,k)*y^k) *x^n/n!.

A091886.name: Values of n such that PrimePi(n)^2 < (e*n*PrimePi(n/e))/log(n), where e = 2.71828...

A091887.name: Irregularity index of the n-th irregular prime A000928(n).

A091888.name: Irregularity index of prime(n): number of numbers k, 1<=k<=(p-3)/2, such that p = prime(n) divides the numerator of the Bernoulli number B(2k).
formula: 0 if p is a regular prime; > 0 if p is an irregular prime

A091889.name: Number of partitions of n into sums of exactly two distinct powers of 2.

A091890.name: Number of partitions of n into sums of exactly three distinct powers of 2.

A091891.name: Number of partitions of n into parts which are a sum of exactly as many distinct powers of 2 as n has 1's in its binary representation.

A091892.name: Numbers k having only one partition into parts which are a sum of exactly as many distinct powers of 2 as there are 1's in the binary representation of k.

A091893.name: Number of partitions of n into numbers having all the same number of 1's in binary representation.

A091894.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of Dyck paths of semilength n, having k ddu's [here u = (1,1) and d = (1,-1)].
formula: G.f.: G = G(t,z) satisfies: t*z*G^2 - (1 - 2*z + 2*t*z)*G + 1 - z + t*z = 0.

With first row zero, the o.g.f. is g(x,t) = (1 - 2*x - sqrt((1 - 2*x)^2 - 4*t*x^2)) / (2*t*x) with the inverse ginv(x,t) = x / (1 + 2*x + t*x^2), an o.g.f. for shifted A207538 and A133156 mod signs, so A134264 and A125181 can be used to interpret the polynomials of this entry. Cf. A097610. - _Tom Copeland_, Feb 08 2016
If we delete the first 1 from the data these are the coefficients of the polynomials p(n) = 2^n*hypergeom([(1 - n)/2, - n/2], [2], x). - _Peter Luschny_, Jan 23 2018

A091895.name: Least number k such that the denominator of d(k)/k = n, or zero if no such number exists.

A091896.name: Numbers n such that there exists no k for which the denominator of d(k)/k = n.

A091897.name: Numbers that remain prime or composite for all permutations of their digits.

A091898.name: Numbers that change from composite to prime or vice versa for at least one permutation of their digits.

A091901.name: Values of n for which sigma(n) < e^gamma * n * log(log(n)).
formula: a(n) = n + 27 for n > 5039, if and only if the Riemann Hypothesis is true. -_Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 31 2011

A091907.name: Numbers n such that (2*n)!/(2*n!)-1 is prime.

A091908.name: Number of interior intersection points made by the straight line segments connecting the edges of an equilateral triangle with the n-1 points resulting from a subdivision of the sides into n equal pieces, counting coinciding intersection points only once.

A091909.name: Numbers n such that (2*n)!/(2*n!)+1 is prime.

A091910.name: Number of distinct distances between the intersection points in A091908 measured from the center of the equilateral triangle.

A091911.name: a(n) = smallest number m such that m*tau(m)/sigma(m) = n, or 0 if no such m exists.

A091912.name: Numerators of Taylor series for log(tan(x)+1/cos(x)).
formula: E.g.f.: sech x or gd x. - Tamas Kalmar-Nagy (integers(AT)kalmarnagy.com), Sep 28 2007

A091913.name: Triangle read by rows: a(n,k) = C(n,k)*(2^(n-k) - 1) for k<n, a(n,k) = 0 for k>=n, where k=0...max(n-1,0).
formula: For k>=n, a(n, k) = 0; for k<n, a(n, k) = C(n, k) * (2^(n-k) - 1) = Sum [C(n,k) * C(n-k, m), {m=1 to n-k}]. [Formula corrected Aug 22 2006]
The triangle (1; 3,2; 7,9,3;...) = A007318^2 - A007318, then delete the right border of zeros. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 16 2007

A091915.name: Maximum of even products of partitions of n.

A091916.name: Maximum of odd products of partitions of n.

A091918.name: Inverse of number triangle A091917.
formula: Binomial transform of triangle A103451: (1; 1,1; 1,0,1; 1,0,0,1;...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 08 2007

A091920.name: Smallest n-digit prime with digits from {1,4,7} only, or 0 if no such prime exists.
formula: a(k) <= minimum(A036931(k), A036934(k), A036944(k)), a(3k) = 0 and a(A004023(k)) = (10^A004023(k) - 1)/9 = A004022(k) for all positive integers k. (The inequality above holds iff a(k) contains at least one of each digit 1, 4 and 7.)

A091921.name: Sum of odd proper distinct prime divisors of n. That is, the sum of odd distinct prime divisors of n that are less than n.
formula: If n is even, a(n) = A008472(n)-2.
If n is prime, a(n) = A008472(n)-n = 0.

A091922.name: Smallest m such that the decimal representation of the m-th prime interpreted in base n is not a prime, but prime in bases 10<=b<n.

A091923.name: Primes whose decimal representations interpreted in base 11 are not prime.

A091924.name: Primes such that their decimal representations interpreted in base 11 are also prime.

A091925.name: Decimal expansion of Pi^3.
formula: Sum_{k >= 0} binomial(2*k,k)/((2*k + 1)^3*16^k) = 7*Pi^3/216. (Kh. Hessami Pilehrood and T. Hessami Pilehrood).

The integer sequences A(n) := 2^n*(2*n + 1)!^3/n!^2 and B(n) := A(n)*( Sum {k = 0..n} binomial(2*k,k)*1/(2*k + 1)^3*(1/16)^k ) both satisfy the second order recurrence equation u(n) = (160*n^4 + 128*n^3 + 144*n^2 + 2)*u(n-1) - 32*(n - 1)*(2*n - 1)^7*u(n-2). From this observation we can obtain the continued fraction expansion 7/216*Pi^3 = 1 + 2/(432 - 32*3^7/(4162 - 32*2*5^7/(17714 - ... - 32*(n - 1)*(2*n - 1)^7/((160*n^4 + 128*n^3 + 144*n^2 + 2) - ... )))). Cf. A002388, A019670 and A093954. (End)
Equals Integral_{x=-oo..oo} x^2/(exp(x/2) + exp(-x/2)) dx. - _Amiram Eldar_, May 21 2021

A091928.name: a(0)=1, a(1)=5; a(n) = 6*a(n-1) + 5*a(n-2) for n > 1.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} 5^k*A122542(n,k). Lim_{n->infinity} a(n+1)/a(n) = 3 + sqrt(14) = 6.741657386773.... - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 22 2006

A091930.name: Write Pi = Sum_{n>=1} 1/sqrt(a(n)), where each a(n) is minimal, unique and the sum approaches Pi from below.

A091931.name: Change the first bit to 0 in binary notation for the n-th prime.

A091932.name: Primes that remain prime when their leading digit in binary representation is replaced by 0.
formula: A118953(A049084(a(n))) = 1; subsequence of A065380. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, May 07 2006

A091934.name: Number of dual isomorphisms on [ n,n* ].

A091935.name: Smallest number of 1's in binary representations of primes between 2^n and 2^(n+1).

A091936.name: Smallest prime between 2^n and 2^(n+1), having a minimal number of 1's in binary representation.

A091937.name: Greatest number of 1's in binary representations of primes between 2^n and 2^(n+1).

A091938.name: Smallest prime between 2^n and 2^(n+1), having a maximal number of 1's in binary representation.

A091939.name: Prime numbers with prime sum of any two digits.

A091940.name: Given n colors, sequence gives number of ways to color the vertices of a square such that no edge has the same color on both of its vertices.
formula: For n > 1, a(n) = floor(n^7/(n^3-1)). - _Gary Detlefs_, Feb 10 2010

A091941.name: a(n) equals the least k that produces the maximum number of partial quotients in the simple continued fraction expansion of (1/n + 1/k).

A091942.name: a(n) equals the maximum number of partial quotients in the simple continued fraction expansion of (1/n + 1/k) for k>=1.

A091943.name: Triangle, read by rows, where T(n,k) equals the least m>0 that produces the maximum number of partial quotients in the simple continued fraction expansion of (1/n + 1/k + 1/m).

A091944.name: Triangle, read by rows, where T(n,k) equals the maximum number of partial quotients in the simple continued fraction expansion of (1/n + 1/k + 1/m) for m>=1.

A091945.name: Numbers n such that there is no k, 0<k<n, satisfying A002487(k)=A002487(n).

A091948.name: Number of values of k, 1<=k<=n, satisfying A002487(k) = A002487(n).

A091951.name: Let R_{k}(m) = the digit reversal of m in base k (R_{k}(m) is written in base 10). a(n) is the smallest m such that R_{k}(m) = n, where k >= 2.

A091954.name: Number of odd proper divisors of n. That is, the number of odd divisors of n that are less than n.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=2} x^k/(1 - x^(2*k)). - _Seiichi Manyama_, Jan 23 2021

A091955.name: Number of increasing subsequences that can be made from the sequence of successive numbers.

A091956.name: Number of increasing subsequences that can be made from the sequence of successive primes.

A091958.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k)=number of ordered trees with n edges and k branch nodes at odd height.
formula: T(n,k) = binomial((n+1), k)*sum((-1)^j*binomial(n+1-k,j)*binomial(2n-3k-3j, n), j=0..floor(n/3)-k)/(n+1). G.f.: G=G(t,z) satisfies (t-1)z^3 G^3 + zG^2 - G + 1 = 0.

A091961.name: Numbers that are not binary cyclic right-rotating progressive sum of digits (see A091821) of any natural number.

A091962.name: From enumerating paths in the plane.
formula: a(n) = det(A*Transpose(A))/36, where A is the 2 X (n+1) matrix whose (i,j)-th element is j^(2*i-1). - _Lechoslaw Ratajczak_, Oct 01 2017

A091963.name: a(n) is the smallest gcd of two interior numbers on row n of Pascal's triangle ("interior" means that the 1's at the ends of the rows are excluded).

A091964.name: Number of left factors of peakless Motzkin paths of length n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} C(n-floor(k/2), floor((k+1)/2)) * C(n-floor((k+1)/2), floor(k/2)). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Mar 24 2005
D-finite with recurrence (n+1)*a(n) + 2*(-n-1)*a(n-1) + (-n+1)*a(n-2) + 2*(-n+3)*a(n-3) + (n-3)*a(n-4) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 24 2012

A091965.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of lattice paths from (0,0) to (n,k) that do not go below the line y=0 and consist of steps U=(1,1), D=(1,-1) and three types of steps H=(1,0) (left factors of 3-Motzkin steps).
formula: G.f.: G = 2/(1 - 3*z - 2*t*z + sqrt(1-6*z+5*z^2)). Alternatively, G = M/(1 - t*z*M), where M = 1 + 3*z*M + z^2*M^2.
Sum_{k>=0} T(m, k)*T(n, k) = T(m+n, 0) = A002212(m+n+1). - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 14 2005

The triangle may also be generated from M^n * [1,0,0,0,...], where M = an infinite tridiagonal matrix with 1's in the super and subdiagonals and [3,3,3,...] in the main diagonal. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 17 2006

A091966.name: Let f(x)=|log x|, f^k(x)=f(f^(k-1)(x))=f iterated k times at x; a(n) = least k such that f^k(n) <= 1/n.

A091967.name: a(n) = n-th term of sequence A_n, or -1 if A_n has fewer than n terms.

A091969.name: Related to Gray codes: see Comments lines.

A091970.name: a(1) = 0; for n>1, find largest integer k such that the word a(1)a(2)...a(n-1) is of the form xy^k for words x and y (where y has positive length), i.e., k = the maximal number of repeating blocks at the end of the sequence so far; then a(n) = floor(k/2).

A091973.name: Poincaré series [or Poincare series] (or Molien series) for a certain three-dimensional group of order 1344.

A091974.name: Let R_{k}(n) = the digit reversal of n in base k (R_{k}(n) is written in base 10). a(n) is the number of distinct values of R_{k}(n) arising if k=2,..,n+1.

A091975.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = largest integer k such that the word a(1)a(2)...a(n-1) is of is of the form xy^(k_1)Y^(k_2)y^(k_3)Y^(k_4)...y^(k_(m-1))Y^(k_m) where y has positive length and Y=reverse(y) and k_1+k_2+k_3+...+k_m = k.

A091976.name: a(1)=1; for n>1, a(n) = largest integer k such that the word a(1)a(2)a(3)...a(n-1) is of the form x(y_1)(y_2)...(y_k) where each y_i is of positive length and any y_i and y_j are related by y_i=P(y_j) for some permutation P.

A091977.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of Dyck paths of semilength n having k exterior pairs.

A091979.name: Number of odd proper distinct prime divisors of n. That is, the number of odd distinct prime divisors of n that are less than n.

A091980.name: Recursive sequence; one more than maximum of products of pairs of previous terms with indices summing to current index.

A091981.name: Poincaré series [or Poincare series] (or Molien series) for GL_2(4):2.

A091982.name: Nonprimes n such that Mod(n,4) == 1 and denominator(Fibonacci((n-1)/4)/n) = 1.

A091984.name: Number of steps required for initial p = 10^n to reach 1 in the recurrence p = floor(Li(p)).
formula: Li(n) = logarithmic integral = integral(x=2..n, dx/log(x)). This gives a very good approximation to the number of primes less than or equal to n. By repeating n=Li(n), n will reach 1 in a finite number of steps.

A091985.name: Number of steps required for the initial value p = 10^n to reach 0 in the recurrence p = pi(p).
formula: pi(n) = A000720(n) = number of primes less than or equal to n. By repeating n=pi(n), n will reach 0 in a finite number of steps.

A091987.name: Number of steps required for initial p = 2^n to reach 0 in the recurrence p = pi(p).
formula: pi(n) = A000720(n) = number of primes less than or equal to n. By repeating n=pi(n), n will reach 0 in a finite number of steps.

A091988.name: Number of steps required for initial p = 2^n to reach 1 in the recurrence p = floor(Li(p)).
formula: Li(n) = logarithmic integral Li(x) = integral(x=2..n, dx/log(x)) ~ pi(n) = number of primes less than or equal to n. Repeating n = Li(n), n will reach 1 in a finite number of steps.

A091990.name: Number of reduced magic borders of order n (these extend magic squares of order n-2 to order n).

A091991.name: Minimal number of 1's that must be inserted into the binary representation of n to get a prime.

A091992.name: Numbers n such that 5*n-3 and 5*n+3 are both primes.

A091996.name: Numbers n such that 9*2^(2*n-1) - 1 is prime.

A091997.name: Numbers n such that 3*2^(n-1) - 1 is prime.

A091998.name: Numbers that are congruent to {1, 11} mod 12.

A092000.name: Numbers that can be expressed as the difference of the squares of primes in exactly four distinct ways.
